P4HE2RPwoovo9QdZAmWY5X_tUSSGFchKnevMYat2WPeGq3wWSiV0wTQUWFi4D6xSgqo0vSU-F-CFJKeCFT01xtU0LWxVGQa_QZ5x4xnkL4MHuzLD0ZtMDX1zUaInf4i3_VL2okrHoKGv8Wn1DFAXvUjcEjp-qPsKdPIR2_g6dmiT4jdrnwzZ-5gxTiryELolh2sB8rhlMvvxgxvAjVbHB7EP1N9-4V29gjhxZRaRyrYs9QwBsLf1tFIj487bxItItN5agjfHt2lkw-QfgImy5-L02mtKzJBbFtbbsaIw2_7EZiw8sKtzsK8p0bS7MwfY7txZZ39FsjcsaJmm-OXx-SpwBs8lOjeX24SRClSnkOHBZ0XgRMAV_h_Y_Skb4-uvJ-xenmTMyUj7bBo6Fc_uSnYVKqCoze-805-KfZxSS3yknEgp95DnOw8rkBXbDo7g6sDOinjLt5CCGnYxsajXPRqkcJy6ENebM8eb8YCst_w1AEDfMmL9XO2sA2nPIUmH_m6pinSuw7cO1JfctChRxs9jnGYfCujmW0iPdORE4Eh2wSmqojM6ApXeicbEySY_jQHL55Kf_XRNI3m7F-GTuT3aVvx2l_RVisPWwJej6XXJjgXIsV8RTxKg0gcs6sYGsI4krPSFqekdcsySF-TKfUaHLU8L9xaBsEkNx97PsKw1wHxE7bI8wRDtZSCCEkNJCDu4Sz5uQx1HQA7l9ob8rwCPcnX4qQ8zWIDFw33qMBdA3DoDUGXXYiLW2yFoRRZE1YRw7jplRw8VbTlolZU6IKADNQsZ2ddfEUlzXXeCLXCY-3us-SmENBhsIuQBAZ8N1wiZIERnJGKDhPEXAAEGyf_Jb-8ViMvrAj0xckEoSfI888gUkZy70oX4xO4EjkTKsbk97ex9gKdcCoEtnvD7YFxd52Ev7lulSY6IK43C511mZRlCUedOcaP0Vnl48FWCTP3vzXgqHOiH3d0zRzIuLablCtAF4M53hW2OL3KMJhceLHu3RzGQHgD8NM3OMMqCF5oqBXgLMDMyA3bWIynFdSEHN_RIWVP9hOQaJjZvZKRBn8Tql6efcy6hFiNAxgw7WSn-yzQ==\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating test class structure**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering whether to use forkEvery=1 to broaden my tests project, but it seems like it might only suit certain situations. The idea of splitting into nested static test classes could work, but I need to stick to the rule of one-to-one mapping between report classes and generated test class files. Also, creating two top-level public tests could create issues, especially with JUnit. I wonder if there’s a way to modify Gradle to help with managing forks effectively.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Analyzing resource handling**\\\\n\\\\nI’m exploring whether resetting is necessary since ResourceBundle.getBundle is called in both overloads when msgs is null. But what happens if a key is missing? In that case, msgs might not be null. I wonder if I can invoke one overload in a Java test and the other in a native test, considering dynamic-access coverage. It seems like coverage reports and dynamic access might be merging from different test tasks, but I’m curious about how this affects method calls across runtimes.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring native image behavior**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about how a native image runtime call could cover specific lines in the executable, but I need to be cautious about using guards. It seems forbidden to skip Native Image execution when using those guards. I wonder if branching based on system properties is a way to manage different behaviors, although it's likely prohibited. There's also the consideration that coverage reports might only reflect JVM agents, not native, but I could use JUnit's lifecycle to manage execution properly in both contexts.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test class structure**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about how to maintain a clear structure between dynamic-access report classes and the generated test class files. One file can have both a test class and a helper that isn't a test, right? I guess we can include a public top-level `CompatibilityTest`, but what about helper classes? If a helper has a main method and isn’t a test, can it be package-private? I feel like all top-level test classes should definitely be public, while a non-test class can be package-private.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating process coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether forking a child process might lack coverage, especially if an agent isn't linked to that child. That's not ideal. I'm also considering launching the same code in a new thread while adjusting the static state, but that doesn't seem right. I wonder if `ResourceBundle.getBundle` doesn't cache the object. The msgs field could be null if it returns null, but it never does. Let's take a look at the dynamic report format to check coverage by line.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_3VBjKtSCSZQRSZzfe4W0CLfT|fc_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fd9d4688197a72d68ad2a3a954c\", \"name\": \"read\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/org.eclipse.platform/org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64/3.133.0/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json\", \"limit\": 200}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 3155, \"output\": 1174, \"cacheRead\": 19968, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 24297, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1780391877194, \"responseId\": \"resp_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fc5f4e08197a0acb6e8cf56d539\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64:3.133.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-02T09-20-17-575998Z.log:1234:[tool-exec] start id=call_3VBjKtSCSZQRSZzfe4W0CLfT|fc_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fd9d4688197a72d68ad2a3a954c name=read args={\"path\": \"tests/src/org.eclipse.platform/org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64/3.133.0/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json\", \"limit\": 200}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64:3.133.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-02T09-20-17-575998Z.log:1240:        \"frame\" : \"org.eclipse.swt.awt.SWT_AWT.lambda$0(SWT_AWT.java:147)\",\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64:3.133.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-02T09-20-17-575998Z.log:1242:        \"metadataType\" : \"reflection\",\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64:3.133.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-02T09-20-17-575998Z.log:1246:        \"frame\" : \"org.eclipse.swt.awt.SWT_AWT.initializeSwing(SWT_AWT.java:83)\",\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.platf