    \\\"totalCalls\\\" : 6\\n  }\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1780391898367}]}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64:3.133.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-02T09-20-17-575998Z.log:1307:[thinking] I'm thinking about working with JVM and how Native Image handles dynamic class loading, which isn't supported. Tests should run natively, but using a classloader approach that needs reflection to call methods seems problematic. I could set Gradle's test configuration to `forkEvery = 1`, but I wonder how to run two methods with forks. Nested test classes might be treated separately by Gradle, and JUnit requires non-static inner classes, which adds some complexity. I need to verify how Gradle scans compiled test files.\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64:3.133.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-02T09-20-17-575998Z.log:1315:[tool-call] delta {\"command\":\"rg \\\"getMessage|msgs|SWTMessages|Compatibility\\\" -n /home/mihailo/git/graalvm-reachability-metadata-copy/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.eclipse.platform/org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64/3.133.0/main/extracted/org/eclipse/swt | head -100\"}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64:3.133.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-02T09-20-17-575998Z.log:1316:[tool-call] end id=call_GqGNGWRgrmAC5VapF34H6oWn|fc_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fe703ac8197828fa2584c0482bd name=bash args={\"command\": \"rg \\\"getMessage|msgs|SWTMessages|Compatibility\\\" -n /home/mihailo/git/graalvm-reachability-metadata-copy/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.eclipse.platform/org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64/3.133.0/main/extracted/org/eclipse/swt | head -100\"}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.win32.win32.x86_64:3.133.0/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-02T09-20-17-575998Z.log:1317:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering testing compatibility**\\n\\nI'm thinking about working with JVM and how Native Image handles dynamic class loading, which isn't supported. Tests should run natively, but using a classloader approach that needs reflection to call methods seems problematic. I could set Gradle's test configuration to `forkEvery = 1`, but I wonder how to run two methods with forks. Nested test classes might be treated separately by Gradle, and JUnit requires non-static inner classes, which adds some complexity. I need to verify how Gradle scans compiled test files.\\n\\n**Analyzing Gradle test detection**\\n\\nI think Gradle's test class detection processes all class files, excluding abstract ones, and might include inner classes. It seems JUnit can run static nested tests, but the @Nested annotation needs to be non-static. If I set `forkEvery=1`, then maybe only the outer class has one fork that includes all nested classes, which doesn't feel reliable. I could explore creating two public top-level test classes in the same Java file, but Java rules say only one must be public—though package-private tests might conflict with that. Am I overlooking something?\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_03e72d197ecc5dca016a1e9fdbd24c81979ef7f6506a7ae2ca\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqHp_n2Voucu6gmaLjDYI_sdPmWWTND1YZE0_-5NOsOhgaDBoKySdWmmYw3E9VemguagwZFbj7O6RRtQ21atgFWMZOnWpiX70mS69chEcyey2eAvAiWrcjRSoogrIzXRIQ5uTki1KYFy9fMQJ61gGv9tieySxP7vMUIV7tD4TyQ7Or3XORVhzuJ3t0E5ph3D0FHHW6aZZuQKDTDK5EVSrPIT85QTaKk6bzEXS7jYge6zCZIumPcU8uh_HZXYtVWFGaY9m1OwfhPC0V3EJjPl2jNSm770JI3Gs_2RbjvRpWOGhFxg665yv8vfe5iFf_2nOab7b95QULwH0N1IeDBYTgn-Uo1vpBYh0JSKWYyr19SIK7KSPTyqOcHoTkhQ60uauGCR_ExtJGKdilCLYCZvgCeXZWZpkbS0UUPposS51iyBoQ69mG2Ioopiw1cmYbJdv2Urebjl0sdRBVKbnbUSNDuDsmSRZIJ9J8qeeb0ka_vcpmoTtYhc_VnNXJtMiwFMBKsBJCoeIanfmJrFCpbukKDIfCCPMjqf6RuYblegLMyzVhc7